book provides an ‘attitudinal/motivational flow-chart’ describing how significant sociopolitical changes affect the language disposition of a nation. The investigation focused on the appraisal of five target languages – English, German, French, Italian and Russian – and this multi-language design made it also possible to observe the changing status of the different languages in relation to each other over the examined 12-year period. Thus, the authors were in an ideal position to investigate the ongoing impact of language globalisation in a context where for various political/historical reasons certain transformation processes took place with unusual intensity and speed. The result is a unique blueprint of how and why language globalisation takes place in an actual language learning environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aIntercultural communicationxHungary. 0aIntercultural communicationzHungary. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teachingxHungary. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teachingzHungary. 0aLanguage awarenessxHungary. 0aLanguage awarenesszHungary. 0aMotivation in education. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh  aHungarian language learners.  aL2 motivation.  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  alanguage attitudes.  alanguage learning.  amotivation.1 aCsizér, Kata, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNémeth, Nóra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311102473808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066313608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014